        <main class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">

            <section class="md:col-span-2 lg:col-span-3 bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-xl p-6 md:p-8">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#073B4C] mb-4">What is Social Constructionism?</h2>
                <p class="mb-6 text-base">The core idea of social constructionism is that our understanding of reality, including abstract concepts like gender, isn't a natural discovery but a product of social and cultural agreement. We collectively build and reinforce what our society considers "normal" or "true." This process turns abstract ideas into concrete societal structures.</p>
                <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center justify-center space-y-4 md:space-y-0 md:space-x-4 text-center">
                    <div class="flowchart-node p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md w-48"><strong>Shared Idea</strong><br/>(e.g., "Boys are strong")</div>
                    <div class="text-4xl flowchart-arrow transform md:-translate-y-2">→</div>
                    <div class="flowchart-node p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md w-48"><strong>Cultural Reinforcement</strong><br/>(Media, Family, Toys)</div>
                    <div class="text-4xl flowchart-arrow transform md:-translate-y-2">→</div>
                    <div class="flowchart-node p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md w-48"><strong>Societal Norm</strong><br/>(e.g., Gender Roles)</div>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section class="lg:col-span-1 bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-xl p-6 md:p-8 flex flex-col">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#073B4C] mb-4">Understanding Intersectionality</h2>
                <p class="mb-6 text-base flex-grow">Coined by Kimberlé Crenshaw, intersectionality is a framework for seeing how different parts of a person's identity—like race, gender, and class—don't just add up. They intersect to create unique, layered experiences of discrimination and privilege that cannot be understood in isolation.</p>
                <div class="relative w-64 h-64 mx-auto flex items-center justify-center">
                    <div class="absolute w-48 h-48 bg-[#FF6B6B] rounded-full opacity-70" style="top: 0; left: 0;"></div>
                    <div class="absolute w-48 h-48 bg-[#FFD166] rounded-full opacity-70" style="top: 0; right: 0;"></div>
                    <div class="absolute w-48 h-48 bg-[#06D6A0] rounded-full opacity-70" style="bottom: 0; left: 50%; transform: translateX(-50%);"></div>
                    <span class="relative z-10 text-white font-bold text-lg text-center">Unique<br/>Lived<br/>Experience</span>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="md:col-span-2 bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-xl p-6 md:p-8">
                 <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#073B4C] mb-4">Fairy Tale Character Tropes</h2>
                 <p class="mb-6 text-base">Classic fairy tales often present highly polarized gender roles. A "Passive Princess" is valued for beauty and virtue, awaiting rescue, while the "Heroic Prince" is defined by action and strength. This chart visualizes the typical traits assigned to these archetypes, showing a stark contrast in expected behaviors and values.</p>
                <div class="chart-container h-[50vh] max-h-[450px]">
                    <canvas id="characterTropesChart"></canvas>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section class="md:col-span-2 lg:col-span-3 bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-xl p-6 md:p-8">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#073B4C] mb-4">Fairy Tales: Mirrors & Shapers</h2>
                <p class="mb-6 text-base">Fairy tales are powerful cultural blueprints. They act as **mirrors**, reflecting the societal gender expectations of the time they were written, and as **shapers**, teaching children what is "expected" of them. This dynamic reinforces and perpetuates cultural norms across generations.</p>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                    <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-[#118AB2]">
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Mirrors of the Past</h3>
                        <p>Classic tales like Cinderella and Snow White reflect a time when a woman's value was tied to beauty, virtue, and securing a beneficial marriage. Their happiness is a reward for passivity and is delivered by an external male character.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-[#06D6A0]">
                         <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Shapers of the Future</h3>
                        <p>Modern adaptations like *Frozen* and *Shrek* challenge these tropes. They introduce heroines with agency, complex motivations, and who find fulfillment through self-discovery and familial bonds, shaping a more inclusive vision of heroism.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="md:col-span-2 lg:col-span-3 bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-xl p-6 md:p-8">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#073B4C] mb-4">The Evolution of the Heroine</h2>
                 <p class="mb-6 text-base">The portrayal of female protagonists in mainstream animated fairy tales has evolved significantly over the last century. This chart tracks the thematic shift from the "Damsel in Distress" trope, where the heroine requires external rescue, to narratives centered on "Female Agency," where the heroine drives her own story and determines her fate.</p>
                <div class="chart-container h-[50vh] max-h-[450px] w-full max-w-full">
                    <canvas id="narrativeEvolutionChart"></canvas>
                </div>
            </section>

